TY  - JOUR
AB  - Elasticity of supply must be carefully distinguished from the slope of the supply curve. Supply curves of simple forms have elasticities varying greatly from point to point, whereas curves with simple elasticity functions (constant, linear) do not seem to satisfy the conditions usually postulated for the supplies of commodities or the factors of production. Elasticity of supply does not indicate relative changes in receipts or costs. For theoretical problems, the slope of the supply curve is more useful as an analytic tool than elasticity of supply.
